## 3 Main results

**Assumption 3.1**.: The design matrix \(\bm{X}\) has i.i.d. rows from \(\mathsf{N}_{p}(\bm{0},\bm{\Sigma})\) for some positive definite matrix \(\bm{\Sigma}\) satisfying \(0<\lambda_{\min}(\bm{\Sigma})\leq 1\leq\lambda_{\max}(\bm{\Sigma})\) and \(\|\bm{\Sigma}\|_{\mathrm{op}}\|\bm{\Sigma}^{-1}\|_{\mathrm{op}}\leq\kappa\). We assume \(\mathrm{Var}[\bm{x}_{i}^{\top}\bm{b}^{*}]\leq\delta^{2}\), that is, the signal of the model (1) is bounded from above.

**Assumption 3.2**.: The noise \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) is independent of \(\bm{X}\) and has i.i.d. entries from a fixed distribution independent of \(n,p\), with \(\mathbb{E}[|\varepsilon_{i}|]\leq\delta\), that is, bounded first moment.

**Assumption 3.3**.: The data fitting loss \(\rho:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}\) is convex, continuously differentiable and its derivative \(\psi\) is 1-Lipschitz and \(|\psi(x)|\leq\delta\) for all \(x\in\mathbb{R}\). The function \(\bm{\phi}_{t}\) is 1-Lipschitz and satisfies \(\bm{\phi}_{t}(\bm{0})=\bm{0}\). The matrices \(\bm{S}_{t}=\sum_{i\in I_{t}}\bm{e}_{i}\bm{e}_{i}^{\top}\), and \(|I_{t}|\geq c_{0}n\) for some positive constant \(c_{0}\in(0,1]\). Let \(\eta_{\max}=\max_{t\in[T]}\eta_{t}\).

Huber loss and Psuedo-Huber loss all satisfy Assumption 3.3.

**Assumption 3.4**.: The data fitting loss \(\rho\) is twice continuously differentiable with positive second derivative.

**Assumption 3.5**.: The sample size \(n\) and feature dimension \(p\) satisfy \(p/n\leq\gamma\) for a constant \(\gamma\in(0,\infty)\).

