### Change of variables

In this section, we conduct the change of variable to simplify the proof. Specifically, we view the linear model \(\bm{y}=\bm{X}\bm{b}^{*}+\bm{\varepsilon}\) as a model with design matrix \(\bm{G}\) and the regression vector \(\bm{\theta}^{*}\), i.e.

\[\bm{y}=\bm{X}\bm{b}^{*}+\bm{\varepsilon}=\underbrace{\bm{X}\bm{\Sigma}^{-1/2 }}_{\bm{G}}\bm{\Sigma}_{\bm{\theta}^{*}}^{1/2}\bm{b}^{*}+\bm{\varepsilon}.\]

This way, the design matrix \(\bm{G}\) has i.i.d. entries from standard normal distribution. Using the same argument in [5, Appendix D], we can show that the matrices \(\bm{H},\bm{F},\widehat{\bm{\Lambda}},\widehat{\bm{K}}\) remains the same under the change of variable. Therefore, we can prove the main results using the model with design matrix \(\bm{G}\) and the regression vector \(\bm{\theta}^{*}\). In other words, we assume without of loss of generality that the design matrix \(\bm{X}\) has i.i.d. \(N(0,1)\), or equivalently that the independent rows of \(\bm{X}\) are normally distributed with covariance \(\bm{\Sigma}=\bm{I}_{p}\). We prove the main results using \(\bm{\Sigma}=\bm{I}_{p}\), and the results for general \(\bm{\Sigma}\) follow by this change of variable with the constant \(C(T,\gamma,\eta_{\max},c_{0},\delta)\) appearing in the bounds depending additionally on \(\kappa\) (the upper bound of the condition number of \(\bm{\Sigma}\) from Assumption 3.1).

### Derivative formulae

In this section, we present derivative formulae that will be useful in later proofs. The following formulas differ from [5] due to the use of robust loss functions and the application of SGD with random batches at each iteration. The formulae are also significantly more complex than in the case of regularized M-estimators [3, 4].

