### Proof of Theorem 3.6

It suffices to prove this theorem for the case \(\bm{\Sigma}=\bm{I}_{p}\). When \(\bm{\Sigma}\neq\bm{I}_{p}\), the result can be derived using a change of variables argument, as outlined in Appendix B.1. By basic algebra, we have

\[\bm{\Theta}_{5}+\|\bm{E}\|_{\mathrm{F}}(\bm{\Theta}_{6}+\bm{\Theta }_{6}^{\top})\] \[=n\bm{H}^{\top}\bm{H}-(\bm{X}\bm{H}-\bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top})^{\top}( \bm{X}\bm{H}-\bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top})+\bm{E}^{\top}(\bm{X}\bm{H}-\bm{F}\bm{W}^{ \top})+(\bm{X}\bm{H}-\bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top})^{\top}\bm{E}\] \[=n\bm{H}^{\top}\bm{H}+\bm{E}^{\top}\bm{E}-(\bm{E}-\bm{X}\bm{H}+ \bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top})^{\top}(\bm{E}-\bm{X}\bm{H}+\bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top})\] \[=n\bm{H}^{\top}\bm{H}+\bm{E}^{\top}\bm{E}-(\bm{R}+\bm{F}\bm{W}^{ \top})^{\top}(\bm{R}+\bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top}).\]

Notice that \(r_{t}=\|\widehat{\bm{b}}^{t}-\bm{b}^{*}\|^{2}+\|\bm{\varepsilon}\|^{2}/n\) is the \(t\)-th diagonal entry of \((\bm{H}^{\top}\bm{H}+\bm{E}^{\top}\bm{E}/n)\), and \(\hat{r}_{t}\) is the \(t\)-th diagonal entry of \((\bm{R}+\bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top})^{\top}(\bm{R}+\bm{F}\bm{W}^{\top})/n\). Since \(\|\bm{E}\|_{\mathrm{F}}=\sqrt{T}\|\bm{\varepsilon}\|\), using the previous display that conditionally on \(\bm{\varepsilon}\), we have

\[\mathbb{E}\Big{[}\big{|}\hat{r}_{t}-r_{t}\big{|}\mid\bm{\varepsilon}\Big{]} \leq n^{-1}\mathbb{E}\Big{[}\|\bm{\Theta}_{5}\|_{\mathrm{F}}+2\|\bm{E}\|_{ \mathrm{F}}\|\bm{\Theta}_{6}\|_{\mathrm{F}}\mid\bm{\varepsilon}\Big{]}=n^{-1} \mathbb{E}\Big{[}\|\bm{\Theta}_{5}\|_{\mathrm{F}}+2\sqrt{T}\|\bm{\varepsilon} \|\|\bm{\Theta}_{6}\|_{\mathrm{F}}\mid\bm{\varepsilon}\Big{]}.\]

Using the moment bounds of \(\bm{\Theta}_{5}\) and \(\bm{\Theta}_{6}\) in Lemma B.6, we have

\[\mathbb{E}\Big{[}\big{|}\hat{r}_{t}-r_{t}\big{|}\mid\bm{\varepsilon}\Big{]} \leq\frac{C(T,\gamma,\eta_{\max},c_{0},\delta)}{\sqrt{n}}\Big{(}1+\frac{\| \bm{\varepsilon}\|}{\sqrt{n}}\Big{)}.\]

Furthermore, if \(\mathbb{E}[|\varepsilon_{i}|]\) is finite, we have by [22] that \(\|\bm{\varepsilon}\|/n\to^{P}0\) (convergence in probability) if \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) has i.i.d. entries with a fixed distribution independent of \(n\). Under this assumption, the right-hand side of the previous display converges to \(0\) in probability. By enlarging the constant if necessary, assume \(C(T,\gamma,\eta_{\max},c_{0},\delta)\geq 1\). To obtain a quantitative bound, by the conditional version of Markov's inequality, for any \(\epsilon>0\), and almost surely with respect to \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) that

\[\mathbb{P}\Big{(}|\hat{r}_{t}-r_{t}|>\epsilon\mid\bm{\varepsilon}\Big{)} \leq\min\Bigl{\{}1,\frac{C(T,\gamma,\eta_{\max},c_{0},\delta)}{ \epsilon}\Big{(}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}+\frac{\|\bm{\varepsilon}\|}{n}\Big{)}\Bigr{\}}\] \[\leq\max\Bigl{\{}1,\frac{C(T,\gamma,\eta_{\max},c_{0},\delta)}{ \epsilon}\Bigr{\}}\min\Bigl{\{}1,\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}+\frac{\|\bm{\varepsilon}\|}{n} \Bigr{\}}.\]Taking expectation with respect to \(\varepsilon\), we obtain

\[\mathbb{P}\Big{(}|\hat{r}_{t}-r_{t}|>\epsilon\Big{)} \leq\max\Big{\{}1,\frac{C(T,\gamma,\eta_{\max},c_{0},\delta)}{ \epsilon}\Big{\}}\mathbb{E}\Big{[}\min\Big{\{}1,\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}+\frac{\| \boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\|}{n}\Big{\}}\Big{]}\] \[\leq\max\Big{\{}1,\frac{C(T,\gamma,\eta_{\max},c_{0},\delta)}{ \epsilon}\Big{\}}\Big{(}\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}+\mathbb{E}\Big{[}\min\Big{\{}1, \frac{\|\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\|}{n}\Big{\}}\Big{]}\Big{)}\]

with \(\mathbb{E}[\min\{1,\frac{\|\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\|}{n}\}]\to 0\) (equivalently, \(\|\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\|/n\to^{P}0\)) if the entries of \(\boldsymbol{\varepsilon}\) are i.i.d. with a fixed distribution independent of \(n\) with \(\mathbb{E}[|\varepsilon_{i}|]<+\infty\) by [22]. This finishes the proof of Theorem 3.6.

